# Scoped Memory Store

## Overview
Develop a secure, reusable, and auditable Scoped Memory Store for LifeOps that provides per-run, per-agent, and global memory scopes with encryption at rest, lifecycle management, and strict schema validation. This system underpins agent-to-agent coordination, traceable conversations, and reversible actions. It powers two key pages: Run Details Page and Agent Trace & Debugger. All components must guard against null/undefined values before using array methods, initialize React state properly for arrays/objects, and validate API responses per the project’s runtime-safety standards.

---

## Components to Build

1) Scoped Memory Store Core
- Purpose: Central storage for memories with scoping, encryption, auditing, and lifecycle policies.
- Scopes:
  - Per-run scope: memories tied to a specific cron/agent run.
  - Per-agent scope: memories scoped to an individual agent.
  - Global scope: memories shared across all agents/runs with access controls.
- Data model:
  - memoryId (string, UUID)
  - scopeType: 'run' | 'agent' | 'global'
  - scopeId: string (runId | agentId | 'global')
  - key: string
  - value: any (encrypted at rest; redactable per field)
  - redactedFields?: string[]
  - ttlMs?: number
  - createdAt: ISO string
  - updatedAt: ISO string
  - encryptionMetadata?: { algorithm: string, keyId: string, encryptedAt: string }
  - auditLog: Array<{ action: 'CREATE'|'UPDATE'|'DELETE'|'READ', actorId: string, timestamp: string, notes?: string }>
- Encryption:
  - Encrypt memory values at rest using envelope encryption with per-scope keys.
  - Include keyId and algorithm metadata for auditing.
- Validation:
  - Enforce schema on write; reject if required fields missing or types invalid.
- Lifecycle:
  - TTL handling per-memory; explicit purge; retention policies with automatic background cleaner.
- API surface (BACKEND):
  - createMemory({ scopeType, scopeId, key, value, ttlMs, redactFields })
  - readMemory({ memoryId } | { scopeType, scopeId, key })
  - updateMemory({ memoryId, value, ttlMs, redactFields })
  - deleteMemory({ memoryId })
  - listMemories({ scopeType, scopeId, filters? })
  - purgeExpiredMemories()
- Auditing:
  - All mutating operations must append to memory auditLog.

2) Run Details Page (page_run_details_010)
- Purpose: Present a comprehensive view of a single cron/agent run with all relevant data and control actions.
- Data Sections:
  - Inputs: trigger payload, variables, scope, constraints, and input prompts.
  - Agent-to-Agent Message Trace: threaded conversation graph showing handoffs, negotiations, alerts, and approvals.
  - Logs: chronological log stream with levels (info, warn, error) and timestamps.
  - Diffs: side-by-side diffs of inputs vs outputs, prompts vs responses, and memory edits.
  - Artifacts: generated artifacts, files, and artifacts metadata (type, size, hash).
  - Timing: start/end timestamps, duration, latency metrics, and per-step timing.
  - Outcome: status (success, failed, canceled), metrics, and human-readable summary.
  - Revert Actions: UI affordance to revert specific actions within the run using a reversible action stack.
- UI Components:
  - RunHeaderCard: high-level run metadata (name, schedule, timezone, status, next run, last run).
  - TimelinePanel: chronological events timeline with collapsible sections.
  - MessageTraceGraph: node-link diagram of agent-to-agent messages; supports zoom/pan; supports filtering by agent or message type.
  - MemoryDiffPanel: show per-memory diffs with redaction indicators and redact/unredact controls.
  - LogsPanel: filterable log viewer with search, severity filter, and export.
  - ArtifactsPanel: grid/list of artifacts with preview, hash, size, and download actions.
  - TimingPanel: latency breakdown and per-step timing bars.
  - RevertPanel: action stack viewer with confirm dialogs and rollback actions.
- Interaction Flows:
  - View details, filter by agent, search logs, inspect messages.
  - Revoke/revert actions with audit trail updates.
  - Redact sensitive fields with policy-enforced toggles.
- Validation & Safety:
  - Ensure all displayed data is sanitized; redactable fields display redaction tokens when needed.

3) Agent Trace & Debugger (page_agent_trace_011)
- Purpose: An interactive debugging console for agent behavior with a visual conversation graph and scoped memory access.
- Features:
  - Visual Conversation Graph: nodes for agents, messages, and actions; edges represent handoffs; interactive exploration with zoom/pan.
  - Scoped Memory View: per-scope memory inspector (run/agent/global) with search, redact controls, and encryption-aware rendering (masked values by default; reveal on explicit user action with audit).
  - Variable States: real-time or replayable snapshots of agent variables and state machines.
  - Step-Through Execution: ability to step through agent reasoning steps, observe state transitions, and annotate rationale.
  - Audit Trail: in-context log of actions, with ability to revert or annotate.
- UI Components:
  - TraceCanvas: canvas/SVG-based graph with draggable nodes, tooltips, and contextual menus.
  - MemoryInspector: collapsible panels for each scope; redactable fields; export/import memory snapshots.
  - StatePanel: shows key-value pairs of agent variables with type hints.
  - Stepper: controls to advance, replay, pause; speed control.
  - AnnotationPanel: add human-readable notes; attach to steps or messages.
- Interactions:
  - Click node to view message payload, provenance, and memory context.
  - Filter graph by agent, type, or time window.
  - Toggle redaction, with an audit log entry for redaction events.
- Validation & Safety:
  - Guard against null memory values; always use (data ?? []) patterns when mapping arrays.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks: React 18+, TypeScript, and a state management approach (React context or Zustand) for cross-page memory access.
- Data Safety:
  - All array-derived UI lists must guard against null/undefined: use Array.isArray(...) and (data ?? []) before .map/.filter/.reduce.
  - Initialize all array state with proper defaults: useState<T[]>([]) for lists; useState<MemoType[]>([]) for memory arrays; avoid useState() without defaults.
- Components & Pages:
  - RunDetailsPage component with subcomponents: RunHeaderCard, InputsPanel, MessageTraceGraph, LogsPanel, DiffsPanel, ArtifactsPanel, TimingPanel, RevertActionsPanel.
  - AgentTraceDebugger component with TraceCanvas, MemoryInspector, StatePanel, Stepper, AnnotationPanel.
  - ScopedMemoryStoreProvider: React context to expose memory APIs to pages, with read/write methods and encryption context.
- API Integrations:
  - Use fetch/axios with null-safe handling: const result = await apiCall(...) ?? {}; const list = Array.isArray(result?.data) ? result.data : [].
  - Ensure all API responses are validated before usage: default to empty arrays/objects if missing.
- Security & UX:
  - Redaction controls in memory inspector; store redacted state with auditability.
  - Permission checks (read/write) enforced client-side for UI affordances; server enforces strictly.
- Accessibility:
  - Ensure keyboard navigability for graph and panels; ARIA labels for interactive elements.

### Backend
- Tech: Node.js/Express or NestJS with PostgreSQL or Supabase-compatible backend; encryption at rest via KMS or envelope encryption.
- Data Models:
  - Memory
    - id, scopeType, scopeId, key, valueEncrypted (bytea/blob), redactedFields text[], ttlMs, createdAt, updatedAt, encryptionMetadata (jsonb), auditLog (jsonb)
  - Run
    - runId, cronJobId, status, startedAt, endedAt, inputs, outputs, trace (jsonb), artifacts (jsonb), logs (jsonb)
  - Agent
    - agentId, name, version, policies
  - MessageTrace
    - messageId, fromAgentId, toAgentId, payload, timestamp, type
  - Artifact
    - artifactId, runId, type, size, hash, location, metadata
  - Audit
    - auditId, subjectId, action, timestamp, details
- Endpoints (rough outline):
  - POST /memories - createMemory
  - GET /memories?scopeType=&scopeId=&key= - list or readMemory
  - GET /memories/:memoryId - readMemory
  - PATCH /memories/:memoryId - updateMemory
  - DELETE /memories/:memoryId - deleteMemory
  - POST /runs - createRun
  - GET /runs/:runId - getRunDetails
  - GET /runs/:runId/logs - getRunLogs
  - GET /runs/:runId/trace - getRunTrace
  - POST /runs/:runId/revert - revertRunAction
  - POST /trace/graph - generateAgentTraceGraph
  - POST /artifacts - storeArtifact
- Security:
  - Enforce per-scope access controls (per-run, per-agent, global) with RBAC.
  - Encrypt memory values at rest; decrypt only on authorized read with auditing.
  - Validate all inputs; enforce schema validation with strict typing.
- Validation:
  - Ensure responses have consistent shapes; guard against nulls like data?.items ?? [].

### Integration
- State Management:
  - ScopedMemoryStoreProvider exposes:
    - getMemory(scopeType, scopeId, key)
    - setMemory(scopeType, scopeId, key, value, ttlMs, redactFields)
    - listMemories(scopeType, scopeId, filter)
    - purgeExpiredMemories()
  - Hooks for components to subscribe to memory changes (optional).
- Data Flow:
  - Run Details page reads run inputs/trace/artifacts via API; uses memory store to redact or reveal fields per policy.
  - Agent Trace & Debugger uses memory inspector to display scoped memory; changes propagate to backend with audit logs.
- Encryption:
  - Encrypt on the backend; frontend should request decryption only for authorized contexts and redact sensitive fields in UI unless user has explicit permission.

---

## User Experience Flow

1) Master Dashboard loads Cronjobs and global memory overview.
2) User selects a Cronjob run from the Run Details page (page_run_details_010).
3) Run Details Page loads:
   - View inputs, agent-to-agent trace, logs, memory diffs, artifacts, timing, outcome.
   - Use Revert Actions to rollback specific steps; confirm with a modal; audit logs update accordingly.
   - Toggle redaction for sensitive memory fields; redactions are tracked in memory audit logs.
4) User navigates to Agent Trace & Debugger (page_agent_trace_011):
   - Interact with the visual conversation graph to inspect messages between agents.
   - Open Memory Inspector to view per-scope memories; redact/unredact with audit trail.
   - Use Stepper to replay or step through agent execution; add annotations for future runs.
5) All actions are auditable; any deletion/reversion flows are reversible within policy constraints; run history and diffs update accordingly.
6) System background tasks purge expired memories in line with TTL and retention policies; dashboards reflect current state with indicators for purged data.

---

## Technical Specifications

Data Models
- Memory
  - id: string (UUID)
  - scopeType: 'run' | 'agent' | 'global'
  - scopeId: string
  - key: string
  - valueEncrypted: string (base64 or binary blob)
  - redactedFields?: string[]
  - ttlMs?: number
  - createdAt: string
  - updatedAt: string
  - encryptionMetadata?: { algorithm: string; keyId: string; encryptedAt: string }
  - auditLog: Array<{ action: 'CREATE'|'UPDATE'|'DELETE'|'READ'; actorId: string; timestamp: string; notes?: string }>
- Run
  - runId: string
  - cronJobId?: string
  - status: 'scheduled'|'running'|'completed'|'failed'|'canceled'
  - startedAt?: string
  - endedAt?: string
  - inputs: object
  - trace: object
  - artifacts: Artifact[]
  - logs: LogEntry[]
  - outcomes?: object
- Agent
  - agentId: string
  - name: string
  - version: string
  - policies: object
- MessageTrace
  - messageId: string
  - fromAgentId: string
  - toAgentId: string
  - payload: object
  - timestamp: string
  - type: string
- Artifact
  - artifactId: string
  - runId: string
  - type: string
  - location: string
  - size: number
  - hash: string
  - metadata?: object
- Audit
  - id: string
  - subjectId: string
  - action: string
  - timestamp: string
  - details?: string

API Endpoints (high-level)
- GET /memories?scopeType=...&scopeId=...&key=...
- POST /memories
- GET /memories/:memoryId
- PATCH /memories/:memoryId
- DELETE /memories/:memoryId
- POST /runs
- GET /runs/:runId
- GET /runs/:runId/logs
- GET /runs/:runId/trace
- POST /runs/:runId/revert
- POST /trace/graph
- POST /artifacts

Security
- Authentication: OAuth2/JWT per LifeOps conventions.
- Authorization: RBAC with per-scope permissions; enforce restrictions for read/write/delete.
- Data protection: encryption at rest with envelope keys; audit trails for all memory mutations; redact fields as policy dictates.
- Input validation: strict schema validation for all API inputs; reject invalid types/fields.

Validation
- Always treat API responses with null-safety: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
- For Supabase-like results: use data ?? [].
- Guard array methods: (items ?? []).map(...), Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
- React state defaults: useState<Type[]>([]) for arrays; useState<Record<string, any>>({}) for objects where applicable.

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Memory operations respect per-scope ACLs and encryption metadata is stored with every memory.
- [ ] All array usages in UI code guard against null/undefined; memory lists render without runtime errors.
- [ ] Run Details Page shows complete inputs, trace, logs, diffs, artifacts, timing, and supports action revert with audit trail.
- [ ] Agent Trace & Debugger provides interactive graph, scoped memory inspector, and step-through execution with proper redaction controls.
- [ ] API responses validated; no undefined values used to drive UI; all list endpoints return [] when no data.
- [ ] TTL and retention policies are enforced in background purge tasks with logs and audit entries.
- [ ] End-to-end tests cover create/read/update/delete memories, run creation and detail views, and debugger interactions.

UI/UX Guidelines
- Apply the LifeOps design system meticulously.
- Maintain the dark, dense, developer-oriented aesthetic.
- Ensure consistent typography, spacing, and micro-interactions as described in the Style sections.
- Visual cues for status, actions, and reversible steps must be clear and accessible.

Visual Style
- Color Palette: as provided (deep near-black backgrounds, subtle surfaces, accent red for active or alerts, teal/amber/purple for data viz)
- Typography: Inter (or SF Pro Display / Roboto fallback), with the specified weights and sizes
- Layout: 8px baseline grid, left sidebar 220–260px, header 56–64px, card paddings 16–20px
- Card Design: elevation, rounded corners, subtle borders/shadows; top icon/thumbnail, then title, then metadata
- Navigation: left compact vertical nav with active states indicated by accent pill and background tint
- Data Visualization: minimal axes, data lines with rounded edges, legends/tooltips with subtle shadows
- Interactive Elements: primary/secondary buttons, inputs, toggles, chips with hover/focus behaviors
- Micro-interactions: 120–200ms transitions, gentle lifts, and easing

